The INV_ASSETS_SOFTWARE table is the auxiliary table that joins the INV_ASSETS table and the INV_SOFTWARE table together in a many-to-many relationship

The INV_ASSETS_TCTOS table is the auxiliary table that joins the INV_ASSETS table and the INV_TCTOS table together in a many-to-many relationship.  The auxiliary table is required solely because of the Many-to-Many relationship.

The INV_ASSETS table defines the attributes of a system at the Serial-Number level and contains dynamic data.  The INV_ASSETS table is the primary table for identifying and tracking assets.  It is used in combination with the INV_SYSTEMS to identify all serially tracked items as well as all non-serially tracked assets which are of importance.  For each and every serially tracked "system" identified by a unique part number, version and cage code in the INV_SYSTEMS table there can be one or more assets associated to that system, each with a unique serial number (each of these assets can only be found in one NHA asset at a time).  For serially tracked items there will be one additional record with a serial number set to "UNKN"  (this replaces the previously used ???????).  This record will be used for serially tracked items which have an unidentifiable serial number  (this asset can be configured in multiple NHA assets at the same time).  For non-serially tracked assets there is a one-to-one relationship between the INV_SYSTEMS table and the INV_ASSETS table.  The serial number (serno) for a non-serially tracked item will be set to "NST" and there will only be one record for that system in the INV_ASSETS table (this asset can be configured in multiple NHA assets at the same time).  The INV_ASSETS table should contain a record for each serially tracked system/part that the RAMPOD system will maintain.

The LU_LOCATIONS table is primarily used as a lookup table to identify several types of locations associated with a asset.  An asset can be owned and there is an owner location associated with the asset owner.  An asset can be assigned to a specific location and there is an assigned location.  An asset is physically located at it's current location and this location may be (but doesn't have to be) the same as its' assigned location,  if the asset has been deployed then the assigned location and current location are different.  Finally an asset may have a maintenance location which differs from the previous three location fields.  The LU_LOCATIONS table is a lookup table that has an entry for each location that RAMPOD refers to at the squadron or company level.  This table was primarily designed into the RAMPOD Core tables for consistency and normalization.

The MAINT_CREWS table holds the names of each worker who performed work during any stage of the repair process.  Crew size can be obtained from obtaining the number of records for a given labor activity (i.e. LABOR_ID).  ).  The tentative plan is for this table will be used for new entries while historical legacy data will be stored in the MAINT_RR_PARTS table in the CREW_CHIEF and CREW_SIZE fields.  One assumption is that there will not be more than one maintenance-chief for any labor activity.  While the table can handle having multiple maintenance-chiefs, the conversion back to CAMS requires no more than one chief.  A requirement from the field was to record the names of all workers working on a repair activity rather than the CAMS requirement of the name of the chief and the total number of workers.

The MAINT_EVENT table is the highest level maintenance table and a new record is entered into this table each time a repairable asset is repaired or has preventative maintenance.  This table primarily defines the problem, what type of problem it is, when the problem was encountered, who (location/unit) is repairing the Pod, what the current status is of the maintenance on the asset, and if the asset becomes fully mission capable.

The MAINT_LABOR table is required after the previous tables define the Problem and the necessary Repair steps, RAMPOD records resources that are utilized in the repair steps.  The primary resource used in any maintenance repair/preventative-step is that of labor.  The MAINT_LABOR table basically defines what labor was expended during a given period of time, what type of labor was it, and what was the outcome of this effort.

The SORTIES table will contain information related to Sorties (flying missions).  The primary information for a sortie is the sortie/mission number.  The sortie/mission number is a 6 character string made of 5 component parts.  The first character represents the month of the year and can be determined by getting the month from the SORTIE_DATE field and obtaining the month code from the LU_CODE for LU_CODE_TYPE.NAME='SORTIE_MONTH_TYPE'.   The second character represents the unit that is flying the mission and is stored in the SORTIE_LOC_CD field and can be obtained from the LU_CODE table where the LU_CODE_TYPE_ID is the one associated with LU_CODE_TYPE.NAME='SORTIE_LOC_TYPE'.   The third character represents the mission type code ( C - Crew Mission, X - Cross Country Mission, D - Deployed Mission) and can be obtained from LU_CODE.VALUE  where the LU_CODE_TYPE_ID is the one associated with LU_CODE_TYPE.NAME='SORTIE_TYPE'.  The fourth and fifth are numeric 01 - 31 to represent the day of the month and can be derived from the SORTIE_DATE field of this table.  Secondary information that will be tracked for each sortie is the time taken to upload and download data from the sortie.
